        </div>
    </div>
    <!-- PLACES TO VISIT SECTION -->
    <div id="feature-section">
        <h1 class="feature-section-title"> The top places to visit in <i>Rajasthan</i></h1>
        <div class="feature-content">
            <div class="cols-3">
                <img src="~/Image/StateImage/Rajasthan/udaipur.jpg">
                <h3> Udaipur </h3>
                <p> Dubbed "the most romantic spot on the continent of India" by British administrator James Tod, Udaipur is a tourist destination and is known for its history, culture, scenic locations and the Rajput-era palaces. </p>
            </div>
            <div class="cols-3">
                <img src="~/Image/StateImage/Rajasthan/ajmer.jpg">
                <h3> Ajmer </h3>
                <p> It is famous for Pushkar Lake and the 14th century Brahma Temple at Pushkar, dedicated to Brahmā, according to the Padma Purāņa, Pushkar is important pilgrimage site for Lord Brahmā. </p>
            </div>
            <div class="cols-3">
                <img src="~/Image/StateImage/Rajasthan/jaisalmer.jpg">
                <h3> Jaisalmer </h3>
                <p> Jaisalmer with its royal forts and palaces has the distinction of being the Golden city of India. One of Rajasthan's biggest tourist destinations. </p>
            </div>
            <div class="cols-3">
                <img src="~/Image/StateImage/Rajasthan/chittorgarh.jpg">
                <h3> Chittorgarh </h3>
                <p> Chittorgarh is home to the Chittor Fort, the largest fort in India and Asia. It was sacked thrice In 1303 by Alauddin Khalji, again in 1535 by Bahadur Shah of Gujarat, and lastly by the Mughal king Akbar in 1568.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
